'''Agallianos Kontoskeles''' ({{lang-el|Ἀγαλλιανός Κοντοσκέλης}}; died 18 April 727) was a [[Byzantine]] military commander and rebel leader.
Agallianos served as ''[[tourmarches]]'' of the [[Theme of Hellas]] in 726/7, when the theme erupted in revolt against Emperor [[Leo III the Isaurian]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Agallianos Kontoskeles (#113)}} Along with Stephen, possibly the commander of the naval district of the [[Cyclades]],{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Stephanos (#6984)}} Agallianos became the leader of the revolt,{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Agallianos Kontoskeles (#113)}} and a certain Kosmas was acclaimed as emperor by the rebels.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Kosmas (#4093)}}
However, the rebel fleet was defeated on 18 April 727 by the loyalist navy through the use of [[Greek fire]]. Agallianos drowned when he fell from the board of his ship into the sea in full armour, while Stephen and Kosmas were captured and beheaded.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Agallianos Kontoskeles (#113)}} On account of his surname "Kontoskeles" ("short-leg"), the ''[[Patria of Constantinople]]'' erroneously involves him in the construction of the [[Kontoskalion]] harbour in [[Constantinople]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Agallianos Kontoskeles (#113)}}
