'''Capital punishment in Uzbekistan''' has been abolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/death-penalty/abolitionist-and-retentionist-countries |title=Abolitionist and retentionist countries &#124; Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-23}}</ref>

On August 1, 2005, President [[Islam Karimov]] signed a decree stating that “the death penalty shall be cancelled in the Republic of Uzbekistan as of January 1, 2008, as a form of criminal punishment and shall be replaced by sentence for life or long prison terms”.
The reason given for the three-year delay  was the need to build new prisons to house people condemned to life terms instead of death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.handsoffcain.info/bancadati/schedastato.php?idstato=17000242 |title=HANDS OFF CAIN against death penalty in the world |publisher=Handsoffcain.info |date=1992-12-08 |accessdate=2014-02-23}}</ref>

The last execution in Uzbekistan took place in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/death-penalty/countries-abolitionist-for-all-crimes |title=Death penalty: Countries abolitionist for all crimes &#124; Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty.org |date=2013-12-18 |accessdate=2014-02-23}}</ref>

