'''James Dinsmore''' (born c. 1771, died 1830) was an Irish carpenter, known for his work while serving [[Thomas Jefferson]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Giordano|first1=Ralph G.|title=The Architectural Ideology of Thomas Jefferson|date=2012|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0786470178|pages=174, 221|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdAxOsdROOQC&pg=PA174&dq=James+Dinsmore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBDgeahUKEwi69sSU3KLHAhWENT4KHVD-DeE#v=onepage&q=%22James%20Dinsmore%22&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> He was responsible for the training of [[John Hemings]], half-brother to [[Sally Hemings]].<ref name=Monticello>{{cite web|title=James Dinsmore|url=http://www.monticello.org/site/plantation-and-slavery/james-dinsmore|publisher=Monticello|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
Dinsmore was born around 1771 or 1772 in [[Ireland]] and he emigrated to the United States during the late 1700s, where he became a naturalized American citizen on June 5, 1798. He was hired by Jefferson in [[Philadelphia]], who paid for Dinsmore's tools and travel expenses to [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref name=UVP>{{cite book|last1=Lay|first1=K. Edward|title=The Architecture of Jefferson Country|date=2000|publisher=University of Virginia Press|isbn=9780813918853|pages=60, 93, 96–99|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XSSUestFtpkC&pg=PA96&dq=James+Dinsmore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAWoVChMI9pTZ3NuixwIVwVY-Ch32Wgk-#v=onepage&q=James%20Dinsmore&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> While at [[Monticello]] Dinsmore worked on the plantation's interior and was responsible for much of the house's woodwork. After 1809 Dinsmore left Monticello to work on [[James Madison|James Madison's]] plantation [[Montpelier (Orange, Virginia)|Montpelier]], where he and [[John Neilson (architect)|John Neilson]] worked on the house's expansion.<ref name=BB>{{cite book|last1=Brookhiser|first1=Richard|title=James Madison|date=2013|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|isbn=9780465063802|pages=134–135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zqMWBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA134&dq=James+Dinsmore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAjgUahUKEwjyrZX226LHAhVCGj4KHR2KBFQ#v=onepage&q=James%20Dinsmore&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> Dinsmore also helped build [[Estouteville (Esmont, Virginia)|Estouteville]] and several of the buildings for the [[University of Virginia]], where he built three pavilions and fourteen dormitories.<ref name=EV>{{cite web|last1=Lay|first1=K. Edward|title=James Dinsmore (1771 or 1772–1830)|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Dinsmore_James_1771_or_1772-1830|publisher=Encyclopedia Virginia|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
Dinsmore died on May 13, 1830 after he drowned in the [[Rivanna River]]. His gravesite is unknown, but is likely in or near [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref name=EV />
