2/15/world/dominican-republic-radio-facebook-shooting-trnd/index.html|title=Dominican Republic radio hosts killed during Facebook Live broadcast|first=Eric Levenson and Sarah Faidell,|last=CNN|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=theweek>{{cite web|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/680243/journalist-killed-broadcasting-facebook-live|title=Journalist killed while broadcasting on Facebook Live|date=14 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>
== Personal life == Luis Manuel Medina was a native of the Dominican Republic, born on March 31, 1968. Medina was raised in [[Consuelo,_Dominican_Republic|Consuelo]], San Pedro de Macorís Province.<ref name=listindiario>{{cite web|url=https://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2017/02/15/454226/crimen-de-dos-locutores-provoca-consternacion|title=Crime of two speakers causes consternation|website=Listin Diario}}</ref> He graduated from the communications program at [[Universidad Central del Este]], a private university in his home province.<ref name=univerzities>{{cite web|url=https://www.univerzities.com/dominican-republic/central-university-of-the-east|title=CENTRAL UNIVERSITY OF THE EAST (UCE)|website=Univerzities}}/</ref> He is buried in Consuelo, San Pedro de Macorís Province.<ref name=listindiario />
== Career == Medina was a broadcast journalist for twenty-five years.<ref name=mediafiledc>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafiledc.com/death-dominican-journalists-shows-dangers-press-freedom/|title=Death of Dominican Journalists Shows Dangers of Press Freedom - MediaFile|date=2 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref> He was employed by ''103.5 HICC'', an FM radio station located in San Pedro de Macorís Province.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-38978627|title=Radio journalists shot dead live on air|date=15 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> At 103.5 FM, Medina co-hosted a popular morning radio program titled ''Milenio Caliente'' (''Hot Millennium'' in English),<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/15/world/americas/arrests-made-in-facebook-live-killing-of-dominican-journalists.html|title=Facebook Live Killing of Dominican Journalists Leads to Arrest of 3 Men|first=Kimiko de|last=Freytas-Tamura|date=15 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> where he often gave live news updates. He also hosted other radio shows for 103.5 FM.<ref name=wtvr>{{cite web|url=http://wtvr.com/2017/02/18/luis-manuel-medina-dead-radio-hosts-leonidas-martinez-killed-facebook-live/|title=Radio hosts killed during Facebook Live|date=19 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Before he worked for 103.5, Medina was employed by ''Radio Dial'' and worked on the news program ''Reportero 670''. Medina was also widely known as the voice of the Dominican professional baseball team, [[Estrellas Orientales]].<ref name=independent>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/two-radio-journalists-shot-dead-facebook-live-dominican-republic-broadcast-leo-martinez-luis-manuel-a7581876.html|title=Two journalists shot dead during Facebook Live broadcast|date=15 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>
== Death == <!--begin wikitable-->{{Location map+ | Dominican Republic | relief = 1 | float = left | position = left | width = 300 | caption = Luis Manuel Medina was fatally shot in his home town, Consuelo, San Pedro de Macorís Province. | alt = Luis Manuel Medina was fatally shot in his home town. | places = {{Location map~ | Dominican Republic | label = Consuelo |lat_deg = 18 | lat_min = 33 | lat_sec= 36 | lat_dir = N | lon_deg = 69 | lon_min = 18 |lon_sec= 00 | lon_dir = W}} }}<!--end wikitable-->Luis Manuel Medina was fatally shot on February 14, 2017, during a Facebook live-streaming broadcast in the ''Centro Comercial del Este'' area.<ref name=washingtontimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/feb/16/facebook-live-captures-four-fatal-shootings-in-one/|title=Facebook Live captures four fatal shootings in one day|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|publisher=}}</ref> The attacker first opened fire on Medina's co-producer, Leonidas Martínez, in the station while Medina was reading the news for a live news update for ''Milenio Caliente''.<ref name=theweek /><ref name=vice>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/story/murder-of-journalists-in-dominican-republic-caught-on-facebook-live|title=Murder of journalists in Dominican Republic caught on Facebook Live|publisher=}}</ref> Gunshots could be heard in the background along with a female voice yelling "Shots! Shots! Shots!"<ref name=apnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/fe502cf644834e1a931d36ff38071254/2-Dominican-journalists-killed-during-live-transmission|title=2 Dominican journalists killed during live transmission|publisher=}}</ref> The attacker then entered the recording studio and shot Medina.<ref name=theweek /> Medina was killed on site, sustaining multiple gunshot wounds.<ref name=thesun>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/2870331/radio-dj-and-producer-shot-dead-by-assassins-while-reading-the-news-on-facebook-live/|title=Radio DJ and producer shot dead by assassins while reading the news on Facebook Live|date=15 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Both Medina and Martínez were killed during the attack. A station secretary, Dayana García de Fernandez, was injured in the stomach and required surgery at the ''Centro Médico Macoríx'', a hospital.<ref name=listindiario /><ref name=cpj>{{cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2017/02/two-radio-journalists-shot-and-killed-during-live-.php|title=Two radio journalists shot and killed during live broadcast in the Dominican Republic - Committee to Protect Journalists|website=cpj.org}}</ref><ref name=huffingtonpost>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/dominican-republic-journalists-killed_us_58a3e18fe4b094a129f0677c|title=2 Journalists Shot Dead In Dominican Republic During Facebook Live Stream|first=Nick|last=Visser|date=15 February 2017|publisher=|via=Huff Post}}</ref> Dominican law enforcement initially arrested three suspects.<ref name=newsmax>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsmax.com/TheWire/luis-manuel-medina-shot-facebook-live-broadcast/2017/02/16/id/773924/|title=Luis Manuel Medina Shot to Death on Facebook Live Broadcast|publisher=}}</ref> The attacker was later identified as José Rodríguez, a 59-year-old man who had a grievance with the pair over either land or as a result of their media work, such as a report from a week earlier about polluted lands.<ref name=mediafiledc /><ref name=theguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/14/journalists-killed-dominican-republic-facebook-live-broadcast|title=Journalists shot dead during Facebook Live video in Dominican Republic|first1=Nina|last1=Lakhani|first2=|last2=agencies|date=14 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>
== Context == The murder of journalists in the Dominican Republic is rare. Since 1997, only four journalists have been killed.<ref name=newsmax/> In Medina's case, there was no immediate motive, although Medina had criticized a political movement in San Pedro de Macorís Province.<ref name=listindiario />
Journalists killed on air or in front of a camera have become more common since 2015. In the [[United States]], journalist [[Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward|Alison Parker]] and camera operator [[Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward|Adam Ward]] were killed on air on August 26, 2015.<ref name=bbc /> The [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] has highlighted the danger to journalists.<ref name=mediafiledc />
== Reactions == {{quote |text=I condemn the murder of Luis Manuel Medina and Leónidas Martínez. Such brutality spreads terror not only throughout the media community of the country concerned but through society at large. I urge the authorities to do all they can to bring those responsible for this crime to trial and support the media whose contribution to the informed public debate is indispensable to maintain respect for internationally recognized human rights, notably the basic right of freedom of expression. |author=[[Irina Bokova]], director-general of [[UNESCO]]<ref name=unesco>{{cite web|url=http://en.unesco.org/news/director-general-condemns-killing-radio-broadcasters-luis-manuel-medina-and-leonidas-martinez|title=Director-General condemns killing of radio broadcasters Luis Manuel Medina and Leónidas Martínez in the Dominican Republic|website=UNESCO}}</ref>}}
{{quote |text=We deeply regret today's events with the death of these communicators, a condemnable and painful act that has appalled the Dominican society. The investigations are underway and we will seek with all the tools at our disposal to find the truth. |author=Jean Rodriguez, Attorney General<ref name=cnn />}}
